Below is a minimal example of how you could invoke the processRequest() method:

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
try {
  // The request text to process
  const promptText = "Everytime after I submit a prompt since June 14, it always triggers websearch. "
    + "Even for simple prompt. Then, in my local langauge, the use of words are always “off”, "
    + "unlike before which seems just fine. What’s even weird is the image generation. "
    + "It will do the web search, then followed by the image";

  // Invoke the API
  const result = api.processRequest(promptText);

  // The returned result is of type ProcessingResult
  console.log("Result:", result);

} catch (error) {
  // If processRequest detects an invalid request, it may throw a ValidationException
  if (error instanceof ValidationException) {
    console.error("ValidationException caught:", error.message);
  } else {
    console.error("An unexpected error occurred:", error);
  }
}
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

In this snippet:
• api.processRequest(promptText) is the main call. 
• request (promptText) is a string that contains the text you want to process. 
• A successful call returns an object of type ProcessingResult, which you can then handle or log. 
• You should be prepared to handle a ValidationException that might be thrown for invalid requests.
